California law gives parties of interest one year from the date the tax collector's deed is recorded to file a claim. Claims are filed directly with the county Tax Collector, not with a court. If you owned the property at the time of sale, or held a qualifying recorded interest such as a mortgage or lien, you may be entitled to some or all of the remaining funds.

The county may ask for documentation showing your right to claim, such as a deed, title report, recorded lien, or other proof required by California Revenue and Taxation Code Section 4675. If the former owner is deceased, heirs may be able to submit an affidavit under California Probate Code Section 13100 in appropriate cases.

California law also requires anyone acting on behalf of a claimant to disclose the amount and source of the excess proceeds and to advise the claimant that the claimant may file directly with the county at no cost. Any assignment of the right to claim excess proceeds must satisfy the requirements in California Revenue and Taxation Code Section 4675.

We can review the county records with you and explain what documentation is typically required for {{ county_name }} County. This letter is informational only and is not legal advice.

